Great call on choosing pnpm. It’s arguably the most efficient way to manage Node on Arch because it avoids the "phantom dependency" mess and disk bloat of standard npm.

On Arch Linux, you have two main ways to go about this. One is "The Arch Way" (using pacman), and the other is the "Modern JS Way" (using pnpm to manage Node itself).

Method 1: The "Modern" Way (Recommended)
This is the cleanest approach. You install a standalone pnpm, and then let pnpm manage your Node versions. This avoids needing nvm or system-wide pacman Node installs that might conflict with project requirements later.

Install pnpm (Standalone):
Open your terminal and run the official script:

Bash
curl -fsSL https://get.pnpm.io/install.sh | sh -
Install Node via pnpm:
Once pnpm is installed, you can install the latest Long Term Support (LTS) version of Node directly through it:

Bash
pnpm env use --global lts
Why this is better: You don't need sudo to install global packages, and you can switch Node versions instantly with pnpm env use --global 22 (or whatever version you need).

Method 2: The "Pacman" Way
If you prefer keeping everything tracked by the Arch package manager, you can install it from the official repos.

Install both:

Bash
sudo pacman -S nodejs pnpm
Does pnpm include node?
No. In the Arch repositories, pnpm lists nodejs as a dependency, but they are separate packages. If you just run sudo pacman -S pnpm, it will automatically pull in nodejs for you because it needs the runtime to function.

Comparison at a Glance
Feature	Method 1 (Standalone pnpm)	Method 2 (Pacman)
Node Versioning	Easy to switch (e.g., pnpm env use)	Locked to Arch repo version
Permissions	User-level (no sudo for globals)	System-level (often needs sudo)
Updates	pnpm self-update	sudo pacman -Syu
Cleanliness	Keeps system folders "pure"	Traditional Linux file structure
💡 Pro-Tip for Arch Users
If you go with the Pacman route (Method 2), you might still find yourself needing a specific older version of Node for a project. In that case, you can still use pnpm env even if you installed pnpm via pacman! pnpm is smart enough to download a local version of Node just for that project or your user profile without messing up your system /usr/bin/node.

