Version Locking: You are tied to whatever version is in the Arch repositories. If Arch updates to Node 23 but your project only works on Node 20, you’re stuck using an AUR helper (like nvm) to fix it.

The "Arch" Philosophy: This is the cleanest for your system (everything is tracked by one database), but often the messiest for development.

The Script Way (Standalone/User-level)
No Sudo: Everything lives in ~/.local/share/pnpm. You never need sudo to update pnpm or install global tools.

Node Version Management: This is the "killer feature." When you install pnpm via the script, it acts as its own version manager. You can run pnpm env use --global 18 and it will swap your Node version instantly without touching your system files.

Isolation: Your development environment is decoupled from your OS. If an Arch update breaks a specific Node library, your pnpm-managed Node remains untouched.

