The Short Answer
Yes, pnpm is smart enough to act as a Node version manager even if pacman installed it. However, you end up with a "redundant" Node installation.

The "Double Node" Scenario
If you run sudo pacman -S pnpm, here is what happens behind the scenes:

Pacman installs nodejs (e.g., v22) to /usr/bin/node. This is the "System Node."

Pacman installs pnpm to /usr/bin/pnpm.

pnpm needs that System Node just to start up and run its own code.

Now, here is the magic (and the mess):
If you then run pnpm env use --global 20:

pnpm downloads Node v20 to ~/.local/share/pnpm/nodejs.

pnpm modifies your shell configuration (.bashrc or .zshrc) to put its own folder ahead of /usr/bin in your $PATH.

When you type node -v, you see v20.

The System Node (v22) is still sitting in /usr/bin/node, gathering dust, only used when pacman needs to verify dependencies.

Why the Script is still "Cleaner"
If you use the sh script, you skip that redundant System Node entirely.

Feature	pacman -S pnpm	sh Script
Node Count	Two (System Node + pnpm-managed Node)	One (Just pnpm-managed Node)
Update Friction	High. If pacman updates Node, it might break global packages until you rebuild them.	Low. You control exactly when Node updates.
System Bloat	Small. You're carrying an extra ~100MB of the System Node you aren't using.	Zero.
The "Pure Arch" Counter-Argument
The only reason to stick with pacman -S pnpm is if you are a purist. Some users hate having binaries in their home folder that the system doesn't know about. If you want pacman -Qi pnpm to actually return a result, use the repo.

My Recommendation
Since you mentioned wanting to avoid "legacy sloth": Use the sh script.

It gives you a "Portable Node" environment. If you ever want to nuking your Node setup, you just delete the ~/.local/share/pnpm folder and your system is back to being pristine. No ghost dependencies left in /usr/lib/node_modules.

