Exactly. If you go the sh route and then decide you'd rather let pacman handle your life, the "cleanup" is almost entirely about your shell configuration.

Here is the "crud" list you'd be looking at:

1. The Directory
As you noted, rm -rf ~/.local/share/pnpm kills the binaries, the downloaded Node versions, and your global packages. This is 95% of the footprint.

2. The Shell Configuration (The "Pollution")
The sh installer is polite but persistent. It appends a block of code to your .bashrc, .zshrc, or .fish/config. It looks something like this:

Bash
# pnpm
export PNPM_HOME="/home/user/.local/share/pnpm"
case ":$PATH:" in
  *":$PNPM_HOME:"*) ;;
  *) export PATH="$PNPM_HOME:$PATH" ;;
esac
# pnpm end
If you don't delete this, your terminal will complain every time you open it because it's trying to add a non-existent folder to your $PATH.

3. The State/Cache Folders
Like most modern CLI tools, pnpm follows the XDG spec. You might find some small leftover files here:

~/.cache/pnpm (Download cache)

~/.config/pnpm (Your personal pnpm settings)

Why "Don't Do Both" is a hard rule
If you have both installed, you enter "Path Hell."

The sh version usually lives in ~/.local/share/pnpm.

The pacman version lives in /usr/bin/pnpm.

Your shell usually checks your Home directory folders before it checks System folders.

You might run sudo pacman -Syu, see pnpm update to v10, but then run pnpm -v and see v9 because the "script" version is still sitting in your Home folder taking priority. It’s a classic source of "Why isn't this feature working?!" frustration.

The "I want to be safe" Workflow
If you're still undecided, start with the sh script. It’s the least intrusive to your Arch system files.

If you hate it:

rm -rf ~/.local/share/pnpm

Open ~/.bashrc (or your shell equivalent) and delete the pnpm block.

sudo pacman -S pnpm

You are then back to a 100% "Arch Way" system with zero leftovers.

